    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.18-19_0001" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">18</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">AGATE SPRINGS STOCK FARM
                        <lb/>
                    JAMES H. COOK, PROPRIETOR
                    -------------------
                    POST OFFICE ADDRESS:</hi> Agate, Sioux County, Nebr.
                    -------------------
                        <lb/>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps"><unclear>PHOTOGRAPH</unclear> AND EXPRESS ADDRESS:</hi> Harrison, Nebr.
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="caps"><unclear reason="missing"></unclear> ADDRESS:</hi> Andrews, Nebr
                        <lb/>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">RANCH COMMISSARY
                        <lb/>
                    AND SUPPLIES</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Mch 3rd 1920</dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear Mr Neihardt</salute>
                    <note type="curatorial">[Bancoft, Nebr.]</note>
                </opener>
                <p>"Your letter of the first just received yesterday" Will be glad to have you come here at anytime you may select., Would expect weather conditions to be much better a week or two later in the season than at the time you have planned for making your trip&#8212; Of course we may have an "early spring"&#8212; and some of the places you mention as having planned to visit are in a lower altitude than here, we have been having a most severe winter here,   If you will send me word as to the time of your coming, when you are far enough along on your trip, to know, I will plan to be at home&#8212;    will plan to have "Big Bat" and "Womans Dress" here if I can when you arrive for I want them to aid you in any way they can&#8212; " Womans Dress" has been very ill recently but is now thought to be getting better.</p>
                
                <p>The Killing of Crazy Horse was witnessed by Womans Dress&#8212; and possibly by "Big Bat", Womans Dress has often told me of the 
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.18-19_0002"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">19</fw>
                    
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">AGATE SPRINGS STOCK FARM
                        <lb/>
                    JAMES H. COOK, PROPRIETOR
                    -------------------
                    POST OFFICE ADDRESS:</hi> Agate, Sioux County, Nebr.
                    -------------------
                        <lb/>
                        
                    <hi rend="caps"><unclear>PHOTOGRAPH</unclear> AND EXPRESS ADDRESS:</hi> Harrison, Nebr.
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="caps"><unclear reason="missing"></unclear> ADDRESS:</hi> Andrews, Nebr
                        <lb/>
                
                    <hi rend="caps">RANCH COMMISSARY
                        <lb/>
                    AND SUPPLIES</hi>
                </fw>
                    
                incident and in Indian style shown me what Crazy Horse did when that bayonet was thrust through him, and what he said when he was suffering and dying from the wound, He kept repeating the words&#8212; "Father, I want to see you."</p>
                
                <p>I write this at this time&#8212; as by the time you might wish to see some of the eye witnesses to that <unclear>incident</unclear> they may be gone&#8212; especially any of the ones who could understand what Crazy Horse was saying, or singing about at that time.</p>
                
                <p>I have never approved of the manner in which a number of prominent Indians were disposed of by <hi rend="caps">U.S.</hi> soldiers in many parts of the west. I think that men such as "Crazy Horse" "Cochise" and "Mangus Colorado," were deserving of a better fate than they received. They certainly viewed the "whites" as invaders&#8212; and they were certainly brave men,</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Most sincerely yours</salute>
                
                    <signed>James H. Cook</signed>
                </closer>
                              
            </div1>
